entry.title: Reconfigure Chrome2023Refresh testing on the bots.
entry.content:
We currently have 3 FYI bots set up to test the

Chrome2023Refresh feature set: {linux,mac,win}-cr23-rel.

They have been running `browser_tests`, `interactive_ui_tests`,

and `views_unittests` with the feature flag enabled.



We want to move this testing to the main waterfall and the CQ

so that we can detect regressions faster and avoid more breakages.

Of course, the main waterfall bots run those suites already,

and so in order to avoid name collisions we'll prefix the

names with 'cr23_', much as we've done before for other

feature testing.



In addition, we are not going to have the capacity to run

the full browser_tests and interactive_ui_tests suites, so

for those two, the cr23_* prefixed test suites will just run

a subset of tests listed in filter files (we will run all

of views_unittests with the flag, however).



To detect more failures off the main waterfall, we'll still

want to run the full test suites as well, so we'll have another

set of renamed suites, `cr23_*_full`. And, in order to make

comparisons easier, we'll also run the normal test suites.



So, this CL changes the 3 FYI bots to run 3 flavors each of

browser_tests and interactive_ui_tests, and 2 flavors of

views_unittests.



Ultimately we'll still want to run the subset test suites with

the flag in the main CI bots and in the CQ, so subsequent CLs

will move those suites to the main CI bots.

entry.title: [//gpu] Eliminate lazy binding in passthrough decoder
entry.content:
Lazy binding in the passthrough decoder exists only on Apple. However,

it is a no-op if the texture doesn't have a GLImage [1], and on Apple

platforms, there is now no way for the texture to have a GLImage (the

only way is to invoke TexturePassthrough::SetLevelImage(), and this is

never called on Mac). This CL does the following:



* Eliminates TexturePassthrough::SetLevelImage() on Mac

* Eliminates LevelInfo holding a GLImage on Mac

* Eliminates lazy binding in the passthrough decoder



There is one subtlety in this removal: This CL removes

`textures_pending_binding_`, which can actually be nonempty on Mac due

to the usage of set_bind_pending() in iosurface_image_backing.mm.

However, the only usage of `textures_pending_binding_` is to make

calls to the lazy binding functionality, which will be no-ops due to the

lack of GLImage present in the texture. In particular, none of the code

being removed calls clear_bind_pending() on the textures due to the

early-out in [1], which occurs before the call to clear_bind_pending()

that would otherwise occur (this is important because

iosurface_image_backing.mm checks is_bind_pending(), so removing any

calls to clear_bind_pending() that are actually executed could change

behavior). Finally, the entries in `textures_pending_binding_` hold on

to their associated TexturePassthrough instances as WeakPtr's, so there

is no risk of any lifetime changes due to their elimination.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:gpu/command_buffer/service/gles2_cmd_decoder_passthrough.cc;l=2070-2084?q=BindOneP&ss=chromium

entry.title: Fix RecordBookmarkOpened() not being called on iOS
entry.content:
RecordBookmarkOpened() records metrics about (unsurprisingly) a

bookmark being opened. It gets called via

BookmarkModel::UpdateLastUsedTime(), but only if the `just_opened`

param is true.



The iOS implementation of HistoryClient did *not* set this param to

true, in contrast to the chrome/ implementation.

This was broken in M111 by crrev.com/c/4137293, which introduced the

`just_opened` param but didn't update the iOS HistoryClient.

This CL fixes that, and thus re-instates related metrics like the

UserAction Bookmarks.Opened on iOS.



(This was an easy mistake to make because the param defaults to false.

As a followup CL, I'll remove the default value.)



Code pointers:



chrome/ HistoryClient (setting `just_opened` to true):

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/refs/heads/main:chrome/browser/history/chrome_history_client.cc;drc=f2c32198ce5251791dc0a79ad63404509c22fee1;l=76



ios/ HistoryClient (leaving `just_opened` as the default false):

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/refs/heads/main:ios/chrome/browser/history/history_client_impl.cc;drc=f2c32198ce5251791dc0a79ad63404509c22fee1;l=95

entry.title: Adjustments and exploratory CHECKs for Win audio capture glitch and delay
entry.content:
Adjustments:

1) Start glitch detection when the stream position moves for the first

time, rather than on a second successful GetPosition call.

2) If qpc position change between two RenderAudioFromSource() calls is

negative (may be caused by a driver bug), clip it to 0.



Exploratory CHECKs, to see what may be causing out of range values for

glitch and delay metrics:

1) the stream position is monotonically non-decreasing (we do not expect

to hit it);

2) the qpc values is monotonically non-decreasing (we may hit it if

there are buggy drivers in the canary/dev population);

3) the qpc-based time received in IAudioClock::GetPosition() is aligned

with base::TimeTicks (we may hit it if GetPosition() returns unexpected

values - for example, on remote desktop: see https://srbug.com/1439283

for a similar audio capture issue).

4) Check that the glitch duration is below 1s and the delay is below 10s

- in case there are other issues not covered by checks 1-3.



The plan is

1) Run this in canary/dev for a bit and collect crash info.

2) Remove CHECKs 1-4 above.

3) Depending on what CHECKs we hit, decide what to do next. Ideally we

should get rid of IAudioClock usage, see http://crbug.com/1453566.

4) If the situation is still unclear - add perfetto tracing for

unexpected glitch and delay UMA values..

entry.title: [Thumbnail Cache] Ignore Aspect Ratio for Refactor
entry.content:
Rather than forcing JPEGs to be of a specific aspect ratio when

captured just capture the viewport and scale it by a factor of 2.



Use a matrix in TabGridViewBinder and MultiThumbnailCardProvider to

correctly crop the bitmap for display. This could use slightly more

memory, but has the upshot of skipping resize entirely and avoid the

need to refetch on rotation changes as the existing bitmap (or the

one being captured) are the best available options anyway.



Based on local testing memory usage was the same within a margin of

5 MB lower for the change. However, in my experience a fluctuation of

up to 10 MB even with forced GC is possible so it is pretty difficult

to say whether this has a net positive or negative effect on memory.

We can observe this during experimentation to see the effect.



When requesting a JPEG do the following:

1) If a capture is in progress wait for it.

2) Otherwise just fetch the JPEG and use a matrix to crop it.



The benefits of this are:

1) We can entirely remove ETC1 decompression and JPEG recompression.

2) Aspect ratio is no longer relevant in the capture code making

it simpler and may be more performant (less bitmap copying).

3) Have some cropped margin for the JPEG so when displayed in the

orientation/aspect ratio the image was not captured for it

doesn't look as unappealing.



Also remove the save_jpeg_thumbnails param. This has been effectively

defaulted to true for a very long time. There is an argument to be

made that on low-end devices where we will show the list version of

the Grid Tab Switcher we could skip recording JPEGs. However, if

we want to do this a better alternative is to just check whether the

device is low-end rather than setting a param.

entry.title: Reland "[ios] Add support for copy-to-surface"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 275f990d792575a0f47866d41aac8ad9e3961fde



To see what I've changed in the reland, please check out:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4600124/1..5



It includes blundell@'s fix from crrev.com/c/4594556 (I'd broken

graphite, accidentally, in my first attempt).



Other noteworthy changes

- We compile out autoscroll-related tests (see comments; I think

the same rationale for ignoring this on Android applies for iOS).

- We ensure that we initialize our screen infos when we construct

our RWHVIOS (without this, we initially have the wrong DSF set).

- We also respect the DSF override (without this, many tests fail).

- We no longer check for integer DSF in ui_resource. In practice,

we should only get integer DSFs, but a handful of tests set non-

integer DSF. We could include "test-only" in these DCHECKs, but

since the ui resource code is robust to non-integer scales (it

finds the nearest applicable resource set), there seems to be no

harm in allowing them.



Original change's description:

> [ios] Add support for copy-to-surface

>

> This exposed a situation where we can have a mismatch in buffer formats

> between compositing and skia, so I've also added plumbing to ensure

> that we don't try to use an unsupported format.

entry.title: Adjust criteria for showing select commands in touch selection menu.
entry.content:
Disable the select all and select word commands in the touch selection

menu if we know that there is no text to select. Also disable the select

all command if we know that all text has already been selected. If we

don't know the text range that can be selected, keep the current

behaviour.



Also fix the behaviour of HandleContextMenu when tapping an empty

textfield while no menu commands are enabled. In this case,

TouchSelectionControllerClientAura does not show a menu but should still

handle the context menu request. (This is just fixing the code initially

added in crrev.com/c/4520088 that didn't account for the select commands

being disabled.)



For testing, just add to the existing browser tests for now. Will add a

tast test and probably also an interactive ui test for the touch

selection menu behaviour in a followup (eventually).

entry.title: Fixes regression in Media.Audio.Processing.CaptureDelayMs
entry.content:
This CL fixes an issue where input audio timestamps were "faked" even

when that was not needed. This leads to very small capture delays

(~1ms) in the AudioProcessor.



With this change, the AP will measure ~10-11 milliseconds on most

audio devices as before.



Note that, there will still be some devices where the QPC-based

timestamp method will not work and that will probably reduce the

Media.Audio.Processing.CaptureDelayMs over time going forward.

entry.title: Reland "[Enrollment] Mock EnrollmentLauncher with a factory."
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 0090223f92fb1a29f3b3ccf2638c382836b69ab3



The problem with original commit was that MockEnrollmentLauncher has to

outlive its tested consumers.



The reland adds better lifetime handling of EnrollmentScreen,

DemoSetupController and MockEnrollmentLauncher in unittests. Browsertest

already have satisfying lifetime.



Now in unit tests, lifetime of mock and tested consumer are managed via

construction order:

1. In EnrollmentScreenUnitTest, mocks are regular non-pointer members

initialized before enrollment screen. Except for MockErrorScreen which

has to be reset in TearDown() before network portal shutdown.

Enrollment screen is also destroyed in TearDown() as it requires

browser process shutdown.

2. In DemoSetupControllerTest, mocks are regular non-pointer members

initialized before tested DemoSetupController.

3. In DemoSetupControllerTest, task environment moved to be the first

member so that all other members (specifically

DemoSetupControllerTestHelper) use it.

4. All mocks are wrapped with NiceMock to prevent unused warnings.



Original change's description:

> [Enrollment] Mock EnrollmentLauncher with a factory.

>

> In tests, enrollment launcher was mocked via global mock holder. Tests
